      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is a very common argument, but most economists believe that manufacturing jobs tend to shift to countries with lower labor costs regardless of whether tariffs are imposed. While taxes might temporarily slow a small portion of job displacement, the long-term consensus suggests they primarily function as a cost transfer, raising prices for consumers and businesses rather than solving the structural issue of global labor cost differences. Additionally, studies show that tariffs often trigger retaliatory measures that further hurt U.S. exporters and companies that rely on imported inputs.",
      "source": "target",
